<section xml:id="section-assignment-week8">
  <title>Week 8 Assignment</title>
  <p><ol>
    <li>
      <p>
        Calculate the following indefinite integrals by using
        linearity, the power rule, and the tables of anti-derivatives.
        (12) 
      </p>
      <p><ol>
        <li><me>
          \int 4^x + x^2 dx
        </me></li>
        <li><me>
          \int x^{\frac{3}{2}} + x^{\frac{5}{2}}dx 
        </me></li>
        <li><me>
          \int \frac{1}{1+x^2} + x^2 dx 
        </me></li>
      </ol></p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Calculate the following definite integrals by using linearity
        and the tables of anti-derivatives. (12)
      </p>
      <p><ol>
        <li><me>
          \int_{0}^{9\pi} \sin x + \cos x dx 
        </me></li>
        <li><me>
          \int_{1}^{e^2} \frac{3}{x} - \frac{2}{x} dx 
        </me></li>
        <li><me>
          \int_{-1}^1 x^3 + 3x^2 - x dx
        </me></li>
      </ol></p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Consider the following integral, for <m>n \in \NN</m>: (6) 
        <me>
          \int_0^1 nx dx 
        </me>
        Calculate this integral for <m>n = 1,2,3,4</m>. Describe what
        is happening to the value of the integrals as <m>n</m>
        increases. By using the fact that the definite integral is the
        area under a curve, geometrically explain the change in this
        integral as <m>n</m> increases. 
      </p>
    </li>
  </ol></p>
